Drunk on corruption
My friend Boris was leaving my place, drunk.
I suggested to him not to drive.
He asked why.
"You've been drinking," I said, "aren't you afraid of the police?"
Boris replied to me: "No, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin; it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped next to it.
Of course, I knew the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris might encounter an officer who wasn't corrupt.
"Impossible," Boris declared, "to get into the police department dealing with traffic, you have to buy your boss's silence.
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your boss's silence?"
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things by the book get mired in administrative red tape.
For $100, you can drive in the city without any restrictions!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for anything.
According to Boris, only those who are not offered them do not accept them.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in disaster or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officers, and even the Kremlin: nobody anywhere is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the prettiest suburbs of Moscow.
This was a luxurious place but similar to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Looking at the pretentious houses decorated with such poor taste, I wondered who owned them and was told that one belonged to an aide to the mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and yet another to the son of the Moscow prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax service official.
Corruption now represents a more serious threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had been fought by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sold weapons and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Groznny and Moscow, the same bus that brought to Moscow the 120 kilograms of explosives used in the siege of the Dubrovka theater, where so many victims perished during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A futile precaution.
Noone controls the buses anymore today.
The driver who didn't know what he was transporting said he was stopped 50 times along his route, always for the same reason.
A policeman would ask him: "Do you know the price?" and the driver would reply: "Of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, or even for entire days on the journey.
The war against Chechnya continues endlessly not only because Chechen rebels have allies like Al-Qaeda and all "international terrorism," but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves who first tax or simply steal from Chechen civilians, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide maps indicating where minefields are, and supply rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels do have stockpiles of ammunition, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not just weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no fight against this scourge has been launched.
To punish corruption more severely?
This would only increase the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are corrupted themselves.
Thus, those called "ordinary people" look upon this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor, "Of course he steals, but look at all he has done for the city!"
Ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the conductor both benefit from this system.
A honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor stopped her, telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy a soldier and he will remove your son's name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any university for a price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive under the influence, commit speeding offenses, ignore red lights, as long as Benjamin Franklin is there to bribe the police.
Alexander Menchikov, minister under Peter the Great, understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When Emperor Peter, disgusted by Russian corruption, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Since then, the situation has worsened over the centuries.
Eliminating corruption might leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the progression of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
